When they offered him in the name of the king what they had brought, he refused everything except some veal and similar kinds of food which his circumstances made necessary Í¾ perfumes, garlands and desserts he distributed among his servants, the rest he ordered to be taken back. Such conduct led the barbarians to hold him in still greater contempt, since they supposed that he had made his choice through lack of acquaintance with fine things.

When Agesilaus was on his way back from Egypt after having received from King Nectenebis two hundred and twenty talents to give as a gift to his country, on arriving at the place called the Port of Menelaus, situated between Cyrene and Egypt, he fell ill and died. Thereupon his friends, in order that his body might the more readjly be taken to Sparta, having no honey,1 covered it with wax and thus bore it to his native land.
